
I. Usability Guidelines: The "Field-Tested" Ruleset
To ensure I.B.I.S. survives the physical realities of an outdoor airsoft deployment, all UX/UI decisions will be strictly governed by the following parameters:
Macro Touch Targets (Tactical Glove Rule): Minimum interactive target size is 64x64px. Interactive elements must have at least 16px of negative space between them. No inline text links for critical actions.
Solar-Max Readability (High-Noon Rule): The mobile application will default to a "Field Light" theme. We will strictly adhere to WCAG AAA contrast ratios (7:1 minimum). Backgrounds will be off-white to reduce glare, with pure black typography and ultra-saturated action colors.
Asynchronous Reliability (Spotty Cell Rule): Every critical mobile flow must be state-aware. The UI must explicitly inform the user if they are "Offline." The QR code generation and the Staff Scanner queue must function locally, with an auto-sync visual indicator (e.g., an amber "Pending Sync" icon) when network connectivity drops.
Linear Tasking (Cognitive Load Limit): The mobile interface will utilize zero-branching progressive disclosure. Users are presented with one mandatory task at a time. Extraneous navigation is hidden until the immediate requirement (e.g., signing a waiver) is complete.
II. I.B.I.S. Core Style Guide
While I cannot see the physical attachments, based on the I.B.I.S. (Command & Control) directive, the visual language must communicate authority, clarity, and precision.
Color Palette (Field-Safe):
Background: Titanium White (#F8F9FA) for mobile glare reduction; Gunmetal (#1A1C1E) for Web Admin dashboards.
Primary Text: Onyx (#0B0C10) on mobile; pure White (#FFFFFF) on web.
Action/Accent: High-Vis Volt Green (#39FF14) for success/go; Hazard Orange (#FF5722) for alerts/pending actions; Crimson (#D32F2F) for errors/missing requirements.
Typography:
Data Readouts & Timestamps: Roboto Mono (Fixed-width for scannability).
Headers & UI Elements: Inter (Highly legible, robust sans-serif).
Component Styling:
Buttons: Brutalist, sharp corners (0px to 2px border radius), 4px solid borders for active states, drop shadows replaced by solid 4px offset borders to ensure visibility in direct sunlight.
Inputs: Thick outlines, large padded input zones, persistent helper text (no vanishing placeholders).
III. Technical Blueprints: Core Application Flows
Below are the architectural specifications for the most critical Phase 1 screens, formatted for immediate developer handoff.
Screen 1: Player Pre-Check Dashboard
Objective: Guide players through mandatory pre-event administrative tasks using progressive disclosure.
Layout Hierarchy: Single-column mobile flexbox. Fixed Top Bar (Event Name, Status), Main Viewport (Task Cards), Bottom Sticky Nav (Disabled until tasks complete).
Component Breakdown:
Status Header: Large typography block displaying overall readiness (e.g., "DEPLOYMENT: PENDING").
Task Card 1 (Ticket): Green border, checkmark icon (Disabled/Completed state).
Task Card 2 (Waiver): Solid Black border, Hazard Orange button "SIGN NOW" (Active state).
Task Card 3 (Gear Check): Greyed out, non-interactive (Disabled state until Waiver is signed).
User Logic: Clicking "SIGN NOW" opens the web-view waiver. Upon successful webhook return, Task 2 transitions to Completed. Task 3 transitions to Active.
Dev Instructions: Use React Native ScrollView. Task cards require dynamic styling based on a boolean isComplete prop. Enforce a minimum height of min-h-24 (Tailwind) for all task cards to meet touch target guidelines.
Screen 2: The Player QR Passport
Objective: Provide a foolproof, locally cached barcode for sub-3-second check-in at the gate.
Layout Hierarchy: Full-screen modal overlay. Hidden UI chrome to maximize screen real estate.
Component Breakdown:
Brightness Override: System-level prompt to push screen brightness to 100%.
QR Canvas: 300x300px QR code component, rendered black on pure white.
Player Identifier: H1 Player Name and H2 Faction/Squad assignment directly below the code.
Wallet Button: "Add to Apple/Google Wallet" (Active state).
User Logic: Screen loads -> App forces max brightness. Code caches to local storage on generation. If cell service drops, the cached SVG/PNG renders automatically.
Dev Instructions: Implement react-native-qrcode-svg. Utilize expo-brightness to handle the system brightness override upon component mount, reverting on unmount.
Screen 3: Staff Scanner Kiosk
Objective: A high-speed, continuous-scanning camera interface that processes players relentlessly and caches offline.
Layout Hierarchy: Z-Index 0: Full-viewport camera feed. Z-Index 1: Tactical HUD overlay (Targeting box, Scan Count, Network Status). Z-Index 2: Transient Feedback Modal (Pass/Fail).
Component Breakdown:
Targeting Reticle: High-contrast yellow brackets outlining the scanning zone.
Network Status Indicator: Top right pill. Green = "Live Sync", Amber = "Offline: X Queued".
Feedback Overlay - CLEAR: Full screen flashes Volt Green with massive white checkmark. Disappears after 1.5s.
Feedback Overlay - HALT: Full screen flashes Crimson. Displays manual override button and text (e.g., "NO WAIVER ON FILE"). Requires physical tap to dismiss.
User Logic: Camera auto-focuses continuously. On QR detection -> Query local DB or Server -> Trigger Feedback Overlay. If Offline -> Log timestamp and ID to local queue -> Trigger Feedback -> Auto-sync queue when network reconnects.
Dev Instructions: Use expo-camera or react-native-vision-camera for low-latency frame processing. The offline queue must utilize SQLite or Async Storage. Do not use complex animations for the Feedback Overlay; use instantaneous state swaps to save processing cycles and maintain sub-3-second speed.

